<h4 class = "page-header">Set Sublime as default editor</h2>
<p><strong>Instruction</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>Be sure that sublime is in your Applications folder.</li>
  <li>Open bash profile.</li>
  <pre>open ~/.bash_profile</pre>
  <li>Place alias within bash profile.</li>
  <pre>alias subl="/Applications/Sublime\ Text.app/Contents/SharedSupport/bin/subl"</pre>
  <li>Reload bash profile to save the changes.</li>
  <pre>source ~/.bash_profile</pre>
  <li>Test that it worked.</li>
  <pre>subl .</pre>
</ol>
<p><strong>Reason</strong></p>
<p>We will be constantly using Sublime editor for all of our code. This is a handy alias that easily opens up sublime for us.</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Install rbenv</h2>
<p><strong>Instruction</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>Download rbenv via brew.</li>
  <pre>brew install rbenv</pre>
  <pre>rbenv init</pre>
  <li>Install the latest version of ruby.</li>
  <pre>rbenv install 2.2.3</pre>
</ol>
<p><strong>Reason</strong></p>
<p>Have stable ruby version to develop on.</p>
